{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1779725330,"nonce":"EVCEp9sGrThMkyLy0TcGmW+ftT4=","message":"Added the GPT-5.5 Pro external review artifact to the results tree in commit `b94cc06` on branch `feature/0b1f109-gpt55-review`:\n\n- `results/0b1f109/notes/gpt-5.5-pro_review.md`\n- Stable git-object reference before merge: `b94cc06:results/0b1f109/notes/gpt-5.5-pro_review.md`\n- Auth request: `6ce57519-dbf2-4db5-b064-218b93e8f7ef`\n\nSummary of the review:\n\nThe reviewer judged the plan scientifically coherent and strongest where it refuses to interpret GRU behavior until the training stack passes a same-game linear round trip against an analytical Riccati target. The core recommendation is to frame the first experiment as a **game-equivalence experiment**, not a behavioral reproduction experiment: can rlrmp/feedbax reproduce the same closed-loop input-output game solved by the finite-horizon H-infinity Riccati recursion?\n\nKey recommended modifications:\n\n- Produce an explicit analytical \"game card\" before training: state vector, delay augmentation, discretization, costs, control scaling, `B_w`, epsilon norm/time integration, gamma/gamma-star convention, LQR/H-infinity gains, nominal trajectories, analytical worst-case disturbance, induced gain, and Delta-v.\n- Split the broad-epsilon gate into two checks: the practical open-loop/trajectory PGD epsilon surrogate and a state-dependent H-infinity adversary or equivalent closed-loop induced-gain computation derived from the Riccati game. Passing only the open-loop surrogate should not be treated as a full same-game certificate.\n- Report a robustness-speed-gain frontier across gamma or epsilon budgets, rather than relying on one point such as `1.5 * gamma_star`. Track Delta-v, feedback gain or standardized step response, induced gain, nominal cost, terminal error, and control energy.\n- Use a transfer matrix rather than a single broad-epsilon-versus-restricted-field contrast. Evaluate trained controllers across clean reach, step-load response, curl fields, orthogonal velocity-dependent fields, broad epsilon induced gain, state-multiplicative perturbations, and held-out adversary searches.\n- Treat restricted-field training as at least potentially two baselines: an Experiment-1-like curl-field distribution and an Experiment-2-like mixed distribution. Worst-case restricted-field training is a separate question unless deliberately chosen as its own arm.\n- Consider a minimal architecture ladder after the linear gate, rather than jumping only from linear regulator to full GRU: affine feedforward plus linear feedback, constrained RNN/GRU with explicit feedback pathway, and GRU variants with or without muscle-like/antagonist-force variables.\n- Later, add a trial-history/meta-policy experiment if the project wants closer contact with the human sequence result, since cs2019 includes next-trial policy shifts and decay after perturbations.\n\nMost important open questions surfaced:\n\n1. Exact discrete-time state vector for the eight-state, six-state, and delay-augmented analytical targets.\n2. Exact `B_w` disturbance channel and whether epsilon enters positions, velocities, force states, all physical states, or a weighted subset.\n3. Whether the training adversary is open-loop trajectory epsilon, state-dependent, or both; if only open-loop, why that is equivalent to the Riccati game.\n4. How gamma maps to the PGD epsilon budget, including timestep scaling in the norm.\n5. Predeclared pass/fail tolerances for gain, trajectory, cost, induced gain, Delta-v, and held-out adversary loss.\n6. Which restricted-field baseline(s) to model: Experiment 1 curl-only, Experiment 2 mixed perturbations, or both.\n7. Whether restricted-field training is expected-cost/domain randomization, minimax over restricted fields, or both as separate arms.\n8. How feedback gain will be measured for nonlinear GRUs: local Jacobians, standardized step responses, induced-gain estimates, or a combination.\n9. What exactly counts as generalization: transfer to unseen physical fields, broad full-state epsilon, state-multiplicative perturbations, or the full cross-evaluation matrix.\n10. What observation would make us abandon the broad-defense-prior interpretation rather than add another training or architecture fix.\n\nThe reviewer also commented briefly on `synthesis-5.md`: it is useful background, but the packet is more careful and should supersede it for the concrete experimental plan.\n\nI also filed dotfiles/Mandible follow-up `04e0397` for first-class repo-relative artifact references in issue comments / ledger surfaces, so future comments do not need to rely on ad hoc `commit:path` notation.","files":null}]}